## Implementation Blueprint

### signal.go structure (package generate, plain `package generate` line — generate.go owns the // Package doc comment, mirroring rescue.go/dedupe.go)
```go
package generate

import (
	"os"
	"os/signal"
	"syscall"

	"github.com/dustin/stagehand/internal/ui"
)

// exit is the process-exit seam. Production leaves it as os.Exit; the signal
// goroutine calls exit(handleSignal(...)). Stdlib Go pattern for testing
// os.Exit in a signal handler.
var exit = os.Exit

// commitSignals is the set the handler arms (PRD §18.4: SIGINT + SIGTERM).
var commitSignals = []os.Signal{syscall.SIGINT, syscall.SIGTERM}

// Package-private state for the single active handler (see Gotcha: one at a time).
var (
	activeCh  chan os.Signal
)

// installSignalHandler arms a SIGINT/SIGTERM handler for the post-snapshot
// phase of CommitStaged (PRD §18.4; reference_impl.md §1 `trap 'handle_error'
// INT TERM`, installed AFTER write-tree, BEFORE generation). On receipt it
// calls ctxCancel (the executor context cancel func — Executor.Run observes
// ctx.Done() and SIGTERM+SIGKILLs the agent's process group via Setpgid),
// then runs rescueFn (a caller-built closure that renders Rescue iff a
// snapshot was taken — TREE gating lives in the closure), then exits with
// ui.ExitRescue (3, PRD §15.4 / P1.M1.T2.S1).
func installSignalHandler(ctxCancel, rescueFn func()) {
	ch := make(chan os.Signal, 1)
	signal.Notify(ch, commitSignals...)
	activeCh = ch
	go func() {
		<-ch
		exit(handleSignal(ctxCancel, rescueFn))
	}()
}

// handleSignal is the testable core of the signal path: cancel → rescue →
// exit code, with NO os.Exit, so unit tests assert side effects + return value
// deterministically. The real exit is performed by the goroutine in
// installSignalHandler via the exit seam.
func handleSignal(ctxCancel, rescueFn func()) int {
	ctxCancel()
	if rescueFn != nil {
		rescueFn()
	}
	return ui.ExitRescue
}

// restoreSignalHandler un-arms the handler and resets SIGINT/SIGTERM to their
// default disposition (PRD §18.4 step 3; `trap - INT TERM`). CommitStaged calls
// it immediately BEFORE git.UpdateRefCAS so a Ctrl-C during the final atomic
// ref update is NOT mistaken for a generation failure (the CAS either fully
// landed or fully failed with HEAD unchanged — neither warrants rescue).
func restoreSignalHandler() {
	if activeCh != nil {
		signal.Stop(activeCh)
		activeCh = nil
	}
	signal.Reset(commitSignals...)
}
```

